..TEXT:
|perch$e~: "That," as the following subjunctive
(|disleghi~) makes clear.  |disleghi~: "Dispel."  |perch$e tu~...
|tuoi~: Cf. Boethius, ^Consol. philos.~ III, ix, 25-28:
..TEXT:
<<<FORMATTING-OFF>>>
     Dissice terrenae nebulas et pondera molis
     Atque tuo splendore mica!  Tu namque serenum,
     Tu requies tranquilla piis, te cernere finis,
     Principium, vector, dux, semita, terminus idem.
..TEXT:
<<<FORMATTING-OFF>>>
     Cast off the earthly weight wherewith I am opprest,
     Shine as Thou art most bright, Thou only calm and rest
     To pious men whose end is to behold Thy ray,
     Who their beginning art, their guide, their bound,
          and way.
..TEXT:
The reader should look closely at the original Latin of Boethius
here, rather than at the English translation, for "terrenae
nebulas" corresponds exactly to Bernard's |nube~, and "pondera
molis" points to what has already been termed the ^mortal pondo~
of the wayfarer (^Par.~ XXVII, 64); see n. to ^Par.~ XXXII,
139.  The living man brings clouds inherent in his mortal
condition to this loftiest of all experiences, to the sight of
God face to face; and these mists must be dispelled, a matter
quite in line with the whole preparation for final vision which
is stated in ^Par.~ XXX, 54, in terms of "making the candle able
to bear the flame."  |co' prieghi tuoi~: It is Bernard's prayer
that Mary, in her turn, should pray for this.
