..TEXT:
|Bernardo m'accennava~... |volea~: Strictly
speaking, the poet is once more guilty of a momentary slip in
maintaining the point of view, a slip that may be compared with
that of ^Purg.~ XXI, 10-12 (which is perhaps the only other
instance of this), for if, as is affirmed, he was "already such
as Bernard desired," he was indeed already completely intent on
gazing into the light, and therefore could not have seen that
Bernard was gesturing and smiling to urge that he do so.
Bernard, in any case, disappears from the reader's attention at
this point, and the poem enters into the simplest of focuses: one
actor (one who would ^see~) and one goal, God.
