..TEXT:
|e l'un~... |reflesso~: One, the second ^giro~,
seems reflected from the first (cf. ^Par.~ XIII, 55-57), just as
one arch of a double rainbow is reflected from the other (cf.
^Par.~ XII, 10-13).  This is the second person of the Trinity,
the Son begotten by the Father, the first ^giro.~  -- |e 'l
terzo~... |si spiri~: This is the third person of the Trinity,
the Holy Ghost, who is, by definition, the love of the Father for
the Son, and of the Son for the Father.  Cf. ^Par.~ X, 2, where
the verb ^spirare~ is used to connote love.  (Cf. also ^Purg.~
XXIV, 53, in this regard.)  |Si~ here is the pleonastic reflexive
stressing identification.  Fire symbolizes love, of course, for
the third person ^is~ Love.  |quinci e quindi~: From the Father
to the Son, and from the Son to the Father.
