..TEXT:
|dentro da s$e, del suo colore stesso~: "Our image,"
Christ incarnate, the Word made flesh, second person of the
Trinity, God who became man, is now exclusively focused upon and
will be all the way to the end -- the mystery of the Incarnation.
How can our mortal flesh be any part of the Godhead, second
person of the Trinity?  And yet Christ has risen in the flesh
(even as Mary, His mother is there, in her body) and flesh in
"our image" ^must~ be here (for our faith ^must~ have it so)!
Cf. ^Par.~ II, 37-42; XXV, 127-128; also Phil. 2:7.  Dante's
phrases are emphatic as they insist on the mystery of the
Word-made-flesh.
